'''Advocacy and incitement''' are two categories of speech, the latter of which is a more specific type of the former directed to producing imminent lawless action and which is likely to incite or produce such action. In the 1957 case ''[[Yates v. United States]]'', Justice [[John Marshall Harlan II]] ruled that only advocacy that constituted an "effort to instigate action" was punishable. 

In the 1969 case ''[[Brandenburg v. Ohio]]'', the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] ruled that a statute that punishes mere advocacy and forbids, on pain of criminal punishment, assembly with others merely to advocate the described type of action, falls within the condemnation of the [[First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution|First]] and [[Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution|Fourteenth Amendments]]. Justice [[Louis Brandeis]] argued in ''[[Whitney v. California]]'' that "even advocacy of violation, however reprehensible morally, is not a justification for denying free speech where the advocacy falls short of incitement and there is nothing to indicate that the advocacy would be immediately acted on." {{law-stub}}

