'''Susan Sherman''' (born 1935) is an American "radical" poet and playwright and the founder of ''[[IKON magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.city-journal.org/html/may-1968-40-years-later-13081.html|title=May 1968: 40 Years Later|date=2015-12-23|work=City Journal|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref>
== Career ==
Sherman's work is connected to the [[Women's liberation movement|Women’s Liberation Movement]] (WLM) in the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lambdaliterary.org/reviews/07/25/the-light-that-puts-an-end-to-dreams-new-and-selected-poems-by-susan-sherman/|title=‘The Light that Puts an End to Dreams: New and Selected Poems’ by...|last=Enszer|first=Julie R.|date=2012-07-25|work=Lambda Literary|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en-US}}</ref> She is a self-proclaimed radical poet. Her poem ''Lilith of the Wildwood, of the Fair Places'' depicts [[Lilith]] as an outlaw figure.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0bPoAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA401&lpg=PA401&dq=%22Susan+Sherman%22+(poet,+playwright,+and+editor)&source=bl&ots=ObqtCDGHDo&sig=NuAl21lYnB8JhIORNWTHyaJov7w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxqp3dgILfAhWmmuAKHWkmCc8Q6AEwBXoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Susan%20Sherman%22%20&f=false|title=Which Lilith?: Feminist Writers Re-Create the World's First Woman|last=Dame|first=Enid|last2=Rivlin|first2=Lilly|last3=Wenkart|first3=Henny|date=1998-09-01|publisher=Jason Aronson, Incorporated|isbn=9781461632535|language=en}}</ref> In addition to writing poetry, plays, and articles, she also was a cultural organizer and worked as an editor and wrote reviews. She was close friends with [[May Sarton]] whos work she edited.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5im6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PT40&lpg=PT40&dq=%22Susan+Sherman%22+poet&source=bl&ots=-dZdjLBXZO&sig=XwTefoCPz4sKaEjf5VpwcHJCbeo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjRyPfxkoLfAhVpTd8KHRnHBjs4FBDoATAAegQIABAB#v=onepage&q=%22Susan%20Sherman%22%20poet&f=false|title=What Is Found There: Notebooks on Poetry and Politics (Expanded Edition)|last=Rich|first=Adrienne|date=2003-10-17|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=9780393348149|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/18/obituaries/may-sarton-poet-novelist-and-individualist-dies-at-83.html|title=May Sarton, Poet, Novelist and Individualist, Dies at 83|last=Gussow|first=Mel|date=|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref> She was also the founder of IKON magazine that ran from 1967 to 1994.<ref name=":0" />

